__toc__

the following problem:
{{IMP/label|probpfppgreen}}
{{IMP/prob|Problem <math>P(f,\phi,\psi)</math>) :
Find <math>u\in U</math> such that:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
 Lu=f \mbox{ in } \Omega
</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u=\phi \mbox{ in } \partial \Omega_1
</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{\partial u}{\partial n_{L}}=\psi \mbox{ in } \partial \Omega_2
</math>}}
with <math>\partial \Omega_1 \cup\partial \Omega_2=\partial \Omega</math>.
}}
Let us find the solution using the Green method. Several cases exist:
===Nucleus zero, homogeneous problem===
{{IMP/label|defgreen}}
{{IMP/defn|The Green solution\index{Green solution} of problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> is the
function 
<math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)</math> solution of: 
{{IMP/label|eqdefgydy}}
{{IMP/eq|<math> 
L{\mathcal G}_y=\delta_y
</math>}}
The Green solution of the adjoint problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> is the function
<math>{\mathcal G}^*_y(x)</math> solution of 
{{IMP/label|eqdefgydyc}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>\overline{L^*{\mathcal G}^*}_y=\delta_y
</math>}}
where horizontal bar represents complex conjugation.
}}
{{IMP/label|theogreen}}
{{IMP/thm|If <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> and <math>{\mathcal G}^*_y</math> exist then
<math>\overline{{\mathcal G}^*}_y(x)= {\mathcal G}_x(y)</math>
}}
{{IMP/pf|
By definition of the adjoint operator <math>L^*</math> of an operator <math>L</math>
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\int \overline{L^*{\mathcal G^*}}_y(r){\mathcal G}_x(r)dr= \int \overline{{\mathcal
G^*}}_{y}(r)L{\mathcal G}_x(r) dr
</math>}}
Using equations  [[#eqdefgydy|eqdefgydy]] and  [[#eqdefgydyc|eqdefgydyc]] of definition [[#defgreen|defgreen]] 
for <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> and <math>{\mathcal G}^*_y</math>,
one achieves the proof of the result.
}}
In particular, if <math>L=L^*</math> then <math>{\mathcal G}^*_x(y)= {\mathcal G}_x(y)</math>.

{{IMP/thm|
There exists a unique function <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> such that
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int {\mathcal G}_x(y) f(x)dx
</math>}}
is solution of Problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L{\mathcal G}_y=\delta_y
</math>}}
}}
The proof<ref>In particular, proof of the existence of <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math>.</ref> of
this result is not given here but note that if 
<math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> exists then:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int \delta_y(x)u(x)=\int \overline{L^*{\mathcal G}^*}_y(x) u(x)dx.
</math>}}
Thus, by the definition of the adjoint operator of an operator <math>L</math>:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x) Lu(x)dx.
</math>}}
Using equality <math>Lu=f</math>, we obtain:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x) f(x),
</math>}}
and from theorem  [[#theogreen|theogreen]] we have:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int {\mathcal G}_x(y) f(x)dx
</math>}}
This last equation allows to find the solution of boundary problem, for any
function <math>f</math>, once Green function <math>{\mathcal G}_x(y)</math> is known.

===Kernel zero, non homogeneous problem===

Solution of problem <math>P(f,\phi,\psi)</math> is derived from previous Green functions:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int \delta_y(x)u(x)dx=\int \overline{L^*{\mathcal G^*}}_y(x)u(x)dx.
</math>}}
Using Green's theorem, one has:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x) Lu(x)dx
+\int_\Gamma  (\bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x)\frac{\partial u}{\partial
n}(x)-u(x)\frac{\partial \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y}{\partial n}(x))dx,
</math>}}
Using boundary conditions and theorem  [[#theogreen|theogreen]], we get:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int {\mathcal G}_x(y) f(x)dx+\int_\Gamma  ({\mathcal
G}_x(y)\phi(x)-\psi(x)\frac{\partial {\mathcal G}_x(y)}{\partial n})dx, 
</math>}}
This last equation allows to find the solution of problem
<math>P(f,\phi,\psi)</math>, for any triplet <math>(f,\phi,\psi)</math>, once Green function
<math>{\mathcal G}_x(y)</math> is known.

===Non zero kernel, homogeneous problem===

Let's recall the result of section  [[secchoixesp|secchoixesp]] :
{{IMP/thm|
If  <math>L^*u_0=0</math> has non zero solutions, and if <math>f</math> isn't in the orthogonal of
<math>\mbox{ Ker }(L^*)</math>, the problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> has no solution.
}}
{{IMP/pf|
Let <math>u</math> such that <math>Lu=f</math>. Let <math>v_0</math> be a solution of
<math>L^*v_0=0</math> ({\it i.e} a function of 
<math>\mbox{ Ker }(L^*)</math>).
Then:
<center><math>\begin{matrix}
 \mathrel{<} f|v_0\mathrel{>} &=& \mathrel{<} Lu,v_0\mathrel{>} \\
       &=& \mathrel{<} u,L^*v_0\mathrel{>}.
\end{matrix}</math></center> 
Thus <math> \mathrel{<} f|v_0\mathrel{>} =0</math>
}}

However, once <math>f</math> is projected onto the orthogonal of <math>\mbox{ Ker }(L^*)</math>, 
calculations similar to the previous ones can be made: Let us assume that the
kernel of <math>L</math> is spanned by a function <math>u_0</math> and that the kernel of
<math>L^*</math> is spanned by <math>v_0</math>.
{{IMP/label|defgreen2}}
{{IMP/defn|The Green solution of problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> is the function
<math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)</math> solution of
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L{\mathcal G}_y=\delta_y-u_0(y)u_0
</math>}}
The Green solution of adjoint problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> is the function
<math>{\mathcal G}^*_y(x)</math> solution of
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\overline{L^*{\mathcal G}^*}_y=\delta_y-v_0(y)v_0
</math>}}
where horizontal bar represents complex conjugaison.
}}
{{IMP/label|theogreen2}}
{{IMP/thm|If <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> and <math>{\mathcal G}^*_y</math> exist, then
<math>\overline{{\mathcal G}^*}_y(x)= {\mathcal G}_x(y)</math>
}}
{{IMP/pf|
By definition of the adjoint <math>L^*</math> of an operator <math>L</math>
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\int \overline{L^*{\mathcal G^*}}_y(r){\mathcal G}_x(r)dr=\int \overline{{\mathcal G^*}}_{y}(r)L{\mathcal G}_x(r)dr
</math>}}
Using definition relations  [[#defgreen2|defgreen2]]
of <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> and <math>{\mathcal G}^*_y</math>, one obtains the result.
}}
In particular, if <math>L=L^*</math> then <math>{\mathcal G}^*_x(y)= {\mathcal G}_x(y)</math>.
{{IMP/thm|
There exists a unique function <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> such that
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u(y)=\int {\mathcal G}_x(y) f(x)dx
</math>}}
is solution of problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> in <math>\mbox{Ker}(L)^\perp</math> and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L{\mathcal G}_y=\delta_y-u_0(y)u_0
</math>}}
}}
Proof<ref>In particular, the existence of  <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math>.</ref> of this
theorem is not given here. However, let us justify 
solution definition formula. Assume that <math>{\mathcal G}_y</math> exists.
Let <math>u_c</math> be the projection of a function <math>u</math> onto <math>\mbox{Ker}(L)^\perp</math>.
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u_c(y)=u(y)-u_0(y)\int \bar{u}_0(x)u(x) dx.
</math>}}
This can also be written:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u_c(y)=\int \delta_y(x)u(x)-u_0(y)\int \bar{u}_0(x)u(x) dx,
</math>}}
or
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u_c(y)=\int \overline{L^*{\mathcal G}^*}_y(x) u(x)dx=\int \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x) Lu(x)dx=\int \bar{\mathcal G}^*_y(x) f(x).
</math>}}
From theorem  [[#theogreen2|theogreen2]], we have:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
u_c(y)=\int {\mathcal G}_x(y) f(x)dx.
</math>}}
   zlxuc olzkyc bjnc oihxc vz8cg

==Resolution==
{{IMP/label|secresolinv}}

Once problem's Green function is found, problem's solution is obtained by
simple integration. Using of symmetries allows to simplify seeking of Green's
functions. 

===Images method===
{{IMP/label|secimage}}
\index{images method}

Let  
<math>U</math> 
be a domain having a symmetry plan: 
<math>\forall x \in U, -x\in U</math>. 
Let 
<math>\partial U</math> 
be the border of 
<math>U</math>.
Symmetry plane shares 
<math>U</math> 
into two subdomains: 
<math>U_1</math> 
and
<math>U_2</math> (voir la figure  [[figsymet|figsymet]]).
{{IMP/label|figsymet}}
[[ Image: Symet.png | center | frame |Domain <math>U</math> is the union of <math>U_1</math> and  <math>U_2</math> symetrical with respect to plane <math>x=0</math>.}]]
Let us seek the solution of the folowing problem:
{{IMP/label|probori}}
{{IMP/prob|Find <math>G_y(x)</math> such that:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
LG_y(x)=\delta(x) \mbox{ in } U_1
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
 G_y(x)=0 \mbox{  on  } \partial U_1
</math>}}
}}
knowing solution of problem
{{IMP/label|probconnu}}
{{IMP/prob|Find <math>G^U_y(x)</math> such that:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
LG^U_y(x)=\delta(x) \mbox{  in  } U
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
 G^U_y(x)=0 \mbox{  on  } \partial U
</math>}}
}}
Method of solving problem  [[#probori|probori]] by using solution of problem [[#probconnu|probconnu]] is called images method  ({{IMP/ref|ma:equad:Dautray1}}).
Let us set <math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)={G}^U_y(x)-{G}^U_y(-x)</math>. Function <math>{\mathcal
G}_y(x)</math> verifies
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L{\mathcal G}_y(x)=\delta(x) \mbox{ in } U_1
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
{\mathcal G}_y(x)=0 \mbox{  on  } \partial U_1
</math>}}
Functions <math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)</math> and <math>G_y(x)</math> verify the same equation. Green
function <math>G_y(x)</math> is thus simply the
restriction of function <math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)</math> to <math>U_1</math>.
Problem  [[#probori|probori]] is thus solved.

===Invariance by translation===

When problem <math>P(f,0,0)</math> 
is invariant by translation, Green function's definition relation can be
simplified. Green function <math>{\mathcal G}_y(x)</math> becomes a function <math>{\mathcal  G}(x-y)</math> 
that depends
only on difference 
<math>x-y</math> 
and its definition relation is:

{{IMP/eq|<math>u(x)=\int {\mathcal G}(x-y)f(y)dx={\mathcal G}*f</math>}}

where <math>*</math> is the convolution product (see appendix{appendconvoldist})\index{convolution}. Function 
<math>{\mathcal G}</math> 
is in this case called
elementary solution and noted <math>e</math>.
Case where 
<math>P(f,0,0)</math>
is translation invariant typically corresponds to infinite boundaries ({{IMP/ref|ma:distr:Schwartz65}}). 

Here are some examples of well known elementary solutions:
{{IMP/exmp|
''Laplace  f equation in <math>R^3</math>.''  Considered operator is:

{{IMP/eq|<math>L=\Delta</math>}}

Elementary solution is:

{{IMP/eq|<math>e(r)=\frac{1}{4\pi r}</math>}}

}}
{{IMP/exmp|
''Helmholtz equation in <math>R^3</math>.''  
Considered operator is: 

{{IMP/eq|<math>L=\Delta+k^2</math>}}

Elementary solution is:
{{IMP/eq|<math>e(r)=\frac{e^{jkr}}{4\pi r}</math>}}
}}

