__toc__
==Variational formulation== {{IMP/label|secvafor}}
Let us consider a boundary problem:{{IMP/prob| Find <math>u\in U</math> such that: {{IMP/label|eqLufva}} {{IMP/eq|<math>Lu(x)=f(x) \forall x \in\Omega</math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math>u(x)=g(x) \forall x\in\partial\Gamma </math>}} }} Let us suppose that is a unique solution <math>u</math> of this problem. For a functional space <math>V</math> sufficiently large the previous problem, may be equivalent to the following: {{IMP/prob| Let us coonsider aboundey problem\
Find <math>u\in U</math> such that: {{IMP/label|eqvari}} {{IMP/eq|<math>\forall v\in V, <v|Lu>=<v|f></math>}} }} This is the variational form of the boundary problem. To obtain the equality [[#eqvari|eqvari]], we have just multiplied scalarly by a "test function" <math><v|</math> equation [[#eqLufva|eqLufva]]. A "weak form" of this problem can be found using Green formula type formulas: the solution space is taken larger and as a counterpart, the test functions space is taken smaller. let us illustrate those ideas on a simple example: {{IMP/exmp| Find <math>u</math> in <math>U=C^2</math> such that: {{IMP/eq|<math>-\Delta u=f, \forall x\in \Omega</math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math>u=g, \forall x\in\partial\Omega </math>}} The variational formulation is: Find <math>u</math> in <math>U=C^2</math> such that: {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall v\in V_1, -\int v\Delta u dx=\int vf dx </math>}} Using the Green equality (see appendix [[secappendgreeneq|secappendgreeneq]])\index{Green formula} and the boundary conditions we can reformulate the problem in: find <math>u\in V</math>, such that: {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall v\in V \int \partial_i v\partial_i u dx=\int vf dx </math>}} One can show that this problem as a unique solution in <math>V=H^1_0(\Omega)</math> where {{IMP/eq|<math> H^1(\Omega)=\{v\in L^2(\Omega);\partial_iv\in L^2(\Omega), 1\leq i\leq n\} </math>}} is the Sobolev space of order 1 on <math>\Omega</math> and <math>H_0^1(\Omega)</math> is the adherence of <math>H^1(\Omega)</math> in the space <math>{\mathcal D}(\Omega)</math> (space of infinitely differentiable functions on <math>\Omega</math>, with compact support in <math>\Omega</math>). }} It may be that, as for the previous example, the solution function space and the test function space are the same. This is the case for most of linear operators <math>L</math> encountered in physics. In this case, one can associate to <math>L</math> a bilinear form <math>a</math>. The (weak) variational problem is thus: {{IMP/label|provari2}} {{IMP/prob| Find <math>u\in V</math> such that {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall v\in V, a(u,v)=L(v) </math>}} }} {{IMP/exmp| In this previous example, the bilinear form is: {{IMP/eq|<math> a(u,v)=\int_\Omega \partial_i u(x)\partial_i v(x) dx. </math>}}
}} There exist theorems (Lax-Milgram theorem for instance) that proove the existence and unicity of the solution of the previous problem [[#provari2|provari2]] , under certain conditions on the bilinear form <math>a(u,v)</math>.
==Finite elements approximation== {{IMP/label|secvarinum}}
Let us consider the problem [[#provari2|provari2]] : {{IMP/prob| Find <math>u\in V</math> such that: {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall v\in V, a(u,v)=L(v) </math>}} }} The method of approximation consists in choosing a finite dimension subspace <math>V_h</math> of <math>V</math> and the problem to solve becomes: {{IMP/label|provari3}} {{IMP/prob|Find <math>u_h\in V_h</math> such that
{{IMP/eq|<math>\forall v_h\in V_h, a(u_h,v_h)=L(v_h)</math>}}
}} A base of <math>\{v_h^i\}</math> of <math>V_h</math> is chosen to satisfy boundary conditions. The problem is reduced to finding the components of <math>u_h</math>:
{{IMP/eq|<math>u_h=\sum_i<v_h^i|u_h>v_h^i</math>}}
If <math>a</math> is a bilinear form
{{IMP/eq|<math>a(u_h,v_h^i)=\sum_j<v_h^i|u_h>a(v_h^j,v_h^i),</math>}}
and to find the <math><v_h^i|u_h></math>'s is equivalent to solve a linear system (often close to a diagonal system)that can be solved by classical algorithms ({{IMP/ref|ma:equad:Ciarlet88}},{{IMP/ref|ma:compu:Press92}}) which can be direct methods (Gauss,Cholesky) or iterative (Jacobi, Gauss-Seidel, relaxation). Note that if the vectors of the basis of <math>V_h</math> are eigenvectors of <math>L</math>, then the solving of the system is immediate (diagonal system). This is the basis of the spectral methods for solving evolution problems. If <math>a</math> is not linear, we have to solve a nonlinear system. Let us give an example of a basis <math>\{v_h^i\}</math>.
{{IMP/exmp| When <math>V=L^2([0,1])</math>, an example of <math>V_h</math> that can be chosen ({{IMP/ref|ma:equad:Ciarlet88}}) is the set of piecewise-linear continuous functions that are zero in <math>x=0</math> and <math>x=1</math> (for Dirichlet boundary conditions). More precisely, <math>L^2[0,1]</math> can be approximated by the space of piecewise linear continuous functions on intervals <math>[i/n,(i+1)/n]</math>, <math>i</math> going from zero to <math>n-1</math>, that are zero in <math>x=0</math> and <math>x=1</math>. The basis of such a space is made by functions <math>(v_h^i), i\in (1,\dots,n-1)</math> defined by:
{{IMP/eq|<math>v_h^i(x)=\frac{i-1}{n}+nx\mbox{ in } [(i-1)/n,i/n]</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>v_h^i(x)=\frac{i}{n}-nx\mbox{ in } [i/n,(i+1)/n]</math>}}
and zero anywhere else (see figure [[#figapproxesp|figapproxesp]]). {{IMP/label|figapproxesp}} [[ Image: Approxesp.png | center | frame |Space <math>L^2[0,1]</math> can be approximated by pice wise linear continuous functions.]] }}
==Finite difference approximation==
Finite difference method is one of the most basic method to tackle PDE problems. It is not strictly speaking a variational approximation. It is rather a sort of variational method where weight functions <math>w_k</math> are Dirac functions <math>\delta_k</math>. Indeed, when considering the boundary problem, {{IMP/label|eqfini}} {{IMP/eq|<math>Lu=f \mbox{ for }x\in \Omega</math>}} instead of looking for an approximate solution <math>u_h</math> which can be decomposed on a basis of weight functions <math>w_k</math>: {{IMP/eq|<math>u_h=\sum_k<w_k|u_h>w_k,</math>}} the action of <math>L</math> on <math>u</math> is directly expressed in terms of Dirac functions, as well as the right hand term of equation [[#eqfini|eqfini]]: {{IMP/label|eqfini2}} {{IMP/eq|<math>\sum (Lu)_{ik} \delta_k=\sum f_k\delta_k</math>}} \begin{rem} If <math>L</math> contains derivatives, the following formulas are used : right formula, order 1: {{IMP/eq|<math> \Delta x\frac{du}{dx}=\sum (u_{i+1}-u_i)\delta_i </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \Delta x^2\frac{d^2u}{dx^2}=\sum (u_{i+1}-2u_i+u_{i+1})\delta_i </math>}} right formula order 2: {{IMP/eq|<math> 2\Delta x\frac{du}{dx}=\sum (-u_{i+2}+4u_{i+1}-3u_i)\delta_i </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \Delta x^2\frac{d^2u}{dx^2}=\sum (-u_{i+3}+4u_{i+2}-5u_{i+1}+2u_i)\delta_i </math>}} Left formulas can be written in a similar way. Centred formulas, second order are: {{IMP/eq|<math> 2\Delta x\frac{du}{dx}=\sum (u_{i+1}-u_{i-1})\delta_i </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \Delta x^2\frac{d^2u}{dx^2}=\sum (u_{i+1}-2u_{i}+u_{i-1})\delta_i </math>}} Centred formulas, fourth order are: {{IMP/eq|<math> 12\Delta x\frac{du}{dx}=\sum (-u_{i+2}+8u_{i+1}-8u_{i-1}+u_{i-2})\delta_i </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> 12\Delta x^2\frac{d^2u}{dx^2}=\sum (-u_{i+2}+16u_{i+1}-30u_i+16u_{i-1}-u_{i-2})\delta_i </math>}} \end{rem} One can show that the equation [[#eqfini2|eqfini2]] is equivalent to the system of equations: {{IMP/label|eqfini3}} {{IMP/eq|<math>\sum_i (Lu)_{ik} =f_k</math>}} One can see immediately that equation [[#eqfini2|eqfini2]] implies equation [[#eqfini3|eqfini3]] in choosing "test" functions <math>v_i</math> of support <math>[x_i-1/2,x_i+1/2]</math> and such that <math>v_i(x_i)=1</math>.
==Minimization problems== A minimization problem can be written as follows: {{IMP/label|promini}} {{IMP/prob|Let <math>V</math> a functional space, a <math>J(u)</math> a functional. Find <math>u\in V</math>, such that: {{IMP/eq|<math>J(u)=\min_{v\in V} J(v)</math>}} }} The solving of minimization problems depends first on the nature of the functional <math>J</math> and on the space <math>V</math>. As usually, the functional <math>J(u)</math> is often approximated by a function of several variables <math>J(u_1,\dots,u_N)</math> where the <math>u_i</math>'s are the coordinate of <math>u</math> in some base <math>E_i</math> that approximates <math>V</math>. The methods to solve minimization problems can be classified into two categories: One can distinguish problems without constraints (see Fig. [[#figcontraintesans|figcontraintesans]]) and problems with constraints (see Fig. [[#figcontrainteavec|figcontrainteavec]]). Minimization problems without constraints can be tackled theoretically by the study of the zeros of the differential function <math>dF(u)</math> if exists. Numerically it can be less expensive to use dedicated methods. There are methods that don't use derivatives of <math>F</math> (downhill simplex method, direction-set method) and methods that use derivative of <math>F</math> (conjugate gradient method, quasi-Newton methods). Details are given in ({{IMP/ref|ma:compu:Press92}}). Problems with constraints reduce the functional space <math>U</math> to a set <math>V</math> of functions that satisfy some additional conditions. Note that those sets <math>V</math> are not vectorial spaces: a linear combination of vectors of <math>V</math> are not always in <math>V</math>. Let us give some example of constraints: Let <math>U</math> a functional space. Consider the space {{IMP/eq|<math>V=\{v\in U, \phi_{i}(v)=0, i\in 1,\dots,n \} </math>}} where <math>\phi_{i}(v)</math> are <math>n</math> functionals. This is a first example of constraints. It can be solved theoretically by using Lagrange multipliers ({{IMP/ref|ma:equad:Ciarlet88}}), \index{constraint}. A second example of constraints is given by {{IMP/eq|<math> V=\{v\in U, \phi_{i}(v)\leq 0, i\in 1,\dots,n \} v</math>}} where <math>\phi_{i}(v)</math> are <math>n</math> functionals. The linear programming (see example [[#exmplinepro|exmplinepro]]) problem is an example of minimization problem with such constraints (in fact a mixing of equalities and inequalities constraints). {{IMP/label|figcontraintesans}} [[ Image: Contraintesans.png | center | frame |Minimization of a function of two variables.]] {{IMP/label|figcontrainteavec]]}} [[ Image: Contrainteavec.png | center | frame |Minimization of a function of two variables with constraints. Here, space is reduced to a disk in the plane <math>u_1,u_2</math>.]] {{IMP/label|figcontrainteaveclag}} [[ Image: Contrainteaveclag.png | center | frame |Illustration of the Lagrange multiplier. At point <math>A</math> tangent vector on the surface and on the constraint curve are not paralele: <math>A</math> does not correspond to an extremum. At point <math>B</math> both tangent vector are colinear: we have an extremum.]] {{IMP/exmp| Let us consider of a first class of functional <math>J</math> that are important for PDE problems. Consider again the bilinear form introduced at section [[secvafor|secvafor]]. If this bilinear form <math>a(u,v)</math> is symmetrical, {\it i.e.} {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall u\in V, \forall v\in V, a(u,v)=a(v,u). </math>}} the problem can be written as a minimization problem by introducing the functional: {{IMP/eq|<math> J(v)=\frac{1}{2}a(v,v)-L(v) </math>}} One can show that (under certain conditions) solving the variational problem:\\ Find <math>u\in V</math> such that: {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall v\in V, a(u,v)=L(v) </math>}} is equivalent to solve the minimization problem:\\ Find <math>u\in V</math>, such that: {{IMP/eq|<math> J(u)=\min_{v\in V} J(v) </math>}} }} Physical principles have sometimes a natural variational formulation (as natural as a PDE formulation). We will come back to the variational formulations at the section on least action principle (see section [[secprinmoindreact|secprinmoindreact]] ) and at the section [[secpuisvirtu|secpuisvirtu]] on the principle of virtual powers. {{IMP/label|exmplinepro}} {{IMP/exmp|Another example of functional is given by the linear programming problem. Let us consider a function <math>u</math> that can be located by its coordinates <math>u_i</math> in a basis <math>e_i</math>, <math>i\in \{1,\dots,N\}</math>: {{IMP/eq|<math> u=\sum u_ie_i </math>}} In linear programming, the functional to minimize can be written {{IMP/eq|<math> F(u)=\sum c_iu_i </math>}} and is subject to <math>N</math> primary constraints: {{IMP/eq|<math> \forall i, u_i\geq 0 </math>}} and <math>M=m_1+m_2+m_3</math> additional constraints: {{IMP/eq|<math> k\in\{1,\dots,m_1\}, \sum_j a_{k,j}u_j\leq b_k, (b_k\geq 0) </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> k\in\{m_1+1,\dots,m_1+m_2\}, \sum_j a_{k,j}u_j\geq b_k\geq 0 </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> k\in\{m_1+m_2+1,\dots,m_1+m_2+m_3\}, \sum_j a_{k,j}u_j=b_k\geq 0 </math>}} The numerical algorithm to solve this type of problem is presented in ({{IMP/ref|ma:compu:Press92}}). It is called the simplex method. }} {{IMP/label|exmpsimul}} {{IMP/exmp|When the variables <math>u_i</math> can take only discrete values, one speaks about discrete or combinatorial optimization. The function to minimize can be for instance (travelling salesman problem): {{IMP/eq|<math> J(u,v)=\sum_{i=1}^N \sqrt{(u_{\sigma(i)}-u_{\sigma(i-1)})^2+ (v_{\sigma(i)}-v_{\sigma(i-1)})^2} </math>}} where <math>u_i,v_i</math> are the coordinates of a city number <math>i</math>. The coordinates of the cities are numbers fixed in advance but the order in which the <math>N</math> cities are visited ({\it i.e} the permutation <math>\sigma</math> of <math>\{1,\dots, N\}</math>) is to be find to minimize <math>J</math>. Simulated annealing is a method to solve this problem and is presented in ({{IMP/ref|ma:compu:Press92}}). }}
==Lagrange multipliers==
Lagrange multipliers method is an interesting approach to solve the minimization problem of a function of <math>N</math> variables with constraints, {\it i. e. } to solve the following problem: \index{contrainte}\index{Lagrange multiplier} {{IMP/prob| Find <math>u</math> in a space <math>V</math> of dimension <math>N</math> such that {{IMP/eq|<math> F(u)=\min_{v\in V}F(v) </math>}} with <math>n</math> constraints, <math>R_i(x)=0, i=1,\dots,n.</math> }} Lagrange multipliers method is used in statistical physics (see section[[chapphysstat|chapphysstat]]). In a problem without any constraints, solution <math>u</math> verifies: {{IMP/eq|<math> dF=0 </math>}} In the case with constraints, the <math>n</math> coordinates <math>u_i</math> of <math>u</math> are not independent. Indeed, they should verify the relations: {{IMP/eq|<math> dR_i=0 </math>}} Lagrange multipliers method consists in looking for <math>n</math> numbers <math>\lambda_i</math> called Lagrange multipliers such that: {{IMP/eq|<math>dL=dF+\sum \lambda_i dR_i=0</math>}} One obtains the following equation system: {{IMP/eq|<math>\frac{\partial F}{\partial x_j}+\sum \lambda_i \frac{\partial R_i}{\partial x_j}=0</math>}}
[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{FULLCHAPTERNAME}}]]

