{{IMP/label|secWKB}}
==Ikonal equation, transport equation==

WKB (Wentzel-Kramers-Brillouin) method\index{WKB method}
is used to show how electromagnetism (Helmholtz equation) implies geometric
and physical optical.
Let us consider Helmholtz equation:
{{IMP/label|eqhelmwkb}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\Delta E+k^2(x)E=0
</math>}}
If <math>k(x)</math> is a constant <math>k_0</math> then solution of  [[#eqhelmwkb|eqhelmwkb]] is:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
E=ce^{-jk_0x}
</math>}}
General solution of equation  [[#eqhelmwkb|eqhelmwkb]] as:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
E=a(x)e^{-jk_0L(x)}
</math>}}
This is variation of constants method. Let us write Helmholtz
equation\index{Helmholtz equation}  using <math>n(x)</math> the optical 
index.\index{optical index} 
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\Delta E+k_0^2n^2(x)E=0
</math>}}
with <math>n=v_0/v</math>.
Let us develop <math>E</math> using the following expansion (see  ([#References|references]))
{{IMP/eq|<math>
E(x)=e^{jk_0[S_0+\frac{S_1}{jk_0}+\dots]}
</math>}}
where <math>\frac{1}{jk_0}</math> is the small variable of the expansion (it corresponds
to small wave lengths).
Equalling terms in <math>k_0^2</math> yields to {\it ikonal equation
:}\index{ikonal equation}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\partial_iS_0\partial_iS_0=n^2
</math>}}
that can also be written:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\mbox{ grad }^2S_0=n^2.
</math>}}
It is said that we have used the "geometrical approximation"\footnote{
Fermat principle can be shown from ikonal equation. Fermat principle is in
fact just the variational form of ikonal equation.
}
. If expansion is limited at this first order, it is not an asymptotic
development  (see  ([#References|references])) of<math>E</math>. Precision is not enough
high in the exponential: If <math>S_1</math> is neglected, phase of the wave is
neglected. For terms in <math>k_0</math>:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\partial_i\partial_iS_0+2\partial_iS_0\partial_iS_1=0
</math>}}
This equation is called transport equation.\index{transport equation} We
have done the physical "optics approximation". We have now an asymptotic
expansion of <math>E</math>.

{{IMP/label|secFermat}}

==Geometrical optics, Fermat principle==

Geometrical optics laws can be expressed in a variational form
\index{Fermat principle} {\it via} Fermat principle (see  ([#References|references])):
{{IMP/prin|''Fermat principle:''  trajectory followed by an optical ray minimizes the
path integral:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L=\int n(\vec r) ds
</math>}}
where <math>n(r)</math> is the optical index\index{optical index} of the considered
media. Functional <math>L</math> is called optical path.\index{optical path}}}

Fermat principle allows to derive the light ray equation
\index{light ray equation} as a consequence of Maxwell equations: 
{{IMP/thm|Light ray trajectory equation is:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{d}{ds}(n\frac{dr}{ds})=\mbox{ grad } n.
</math>}}
}}
{{IMP/pf|Let us parametrize optical path by some <math>t</math> variable:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L=\int_{t_1}^{t_2} n(\vec r) \frac{ds}{dt}dt
</math>}}
Setting:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
M(\dot{\vec r})=\frac{ds}{dt} 
</math>}}
yields:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L(\vec r)=\int_{t_1}^{t_2} n(\vec r) M(\dot{\vec r})dt.
</math>}}
Optical path <math>L</math> can thus be written:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L=\int_{t_1}^{t_2} F(\vec r,\dot{\vec r})dt
</math>}}
Let us calculate variations of <math>L</math>:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
0=L(\vec r + \vec u)-L(\vec r )=\int_{t_1}^{t_2} (\frac{\partial
n}{\partial \vec r} M(\dot{\vec r}) \vec u+n(\vec r) \frac{\partial
M}{\partial \dot{\vec r}}\dot{\vec u}) dt
</math>}}
Integrating by parts the second term:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\int_{t_1}^{t_2}n(\vec r) \frac{\partial M}{\partial \dot{\vec
r}}\dot{\vec u} dt=[]+\frac{d}{dt}( \frac{\partial M}{\partial \dot{\vec
r}})\vec u
</math>}}
Now we have:\footnote{
Indeed
{{IMP/eq|<math>
M(\dot x,\dot y, \dot z)=\sqrt{\dot x^2+\dot y^2+\dot z^2}
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{\partial M}{\partial \dot x}=\frac{\dot x}{\sqrt{\dot x^2+\dot y^2+\dot z^2}}=\frac{dx}{ds}
</math>}}
}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{\partial M}{\partial \dot{\vec r}}=\frac{d\vec r}{ds}
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{d}{dt}={M(\dot{\vec r})}\frac{1}{ds}
</math>}}
so:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{d}{ds}(n\frac{dr}{ds})=\mbox{ grad } n
</math>}}
This is the light ray equation.
}}
{{IMP/rem|
Snell-Descartes laws\index{Snell--Descartes law} can be deduced from Fermat
principle. Consider the space shared into two parts by a surface <math>S</math>; part
above <math>S</math> has index <math>n_1</math> and part under <math>S</math> has index <math>n_2</math>. Let <math>I</math>
be a point of <math>S</math>. Consider 
<math>A_1</math> a point of medium <math>1</math> and <math>A_2</math>  a point of medium <math>2</math>. Let us introduce
optical path\footnote{Inside each medium <math>1</math> and <math>2</math>, Fermat principle application shows that light propagates as a line}.
{{IMP/eq|<math>
L=n_1\vec{A_1I}.\vec{u}_1+n_2\vec{IA_2}.\vec{u}_2
</math>}}
where <math>\vec{u}_1=\frac {\vec{A_1I}}{|A_1I|}</math> and <math>\vec{u}_2=\frac
{\vec{A_2I}}{|A_2I|}</math> are unit vectors (see figure  [[#figfermat|figfermat]]). 

{{IMP/label|figfermat}}
[[ Image: Fermat.png | center | frame |Snell-Descartes laws can be deduced from fermat principle.]]
From Fermat principle, <math>dL=0</math>.
As <math>u_1</math> is unitary <math>\vec{u}_1.d\vec{u}_1=0</math>, and it yields:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
0=(n_2u_2-n_1u_1).d\vec{I}.
</math>}}
This last equality is verified by each <math>d\vec{I}</math> belonging to the surface:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
(n_2\vec{u}_2-n_1\vec{u}_1).\vec t=0
</math>}}
where <math>\vec t</math> is tangent vector of surface. This is Snell-Descartes equation.
}}
Another equation of geometrical optics is ikonal equation.\index{ikonal equation} 
{{IMP/thm|Ikonal equation
{{IMP/eq|<math>
n\frac{dr}{ds}=\mbox{ grad } L
</math>}}
is equivalent to light ray equation:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{d}{ds}(n\frac{dr}{ds})=\mbox{ grad } n
</math>}}
}}
{{IMP/pf|
Let us differentiate ikonal equation with respect to <math>s</math> (see ([#References|references])): 
<center><math>\begin{matrix}
\frac{d}{ds}(n\frac{dr}{ds})&=&\frac{d}{ds} \mbox{ grad } L\\
&=&\frac{dr}{ds} \mbox{ grad }(\mbox{ grad } L)\\
&=&\frac{1}{n} \mbox{ grad } L  \mbox{ grad }(\mbox{ grad } L)\\
&=&\frac{1}{2n} \mbox{ grad } n^2
\end{matrix}</math></center>
So:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{d}{ds}(n\frac{dr}{ds})=\mbox{ grad } n
</math>}}
This is light ray equation.
}}
Fermat principle is so a consequence of Maxwell equations.

{{IMP/label|secdiffra}}

==Physical optics, Diffraction==

===Problem position===

Consider a screen <math>S_1</math> with a hole\index{diffraction} <math>\Sigma</math> inside it. Complementar of <math>\Sigma</math> in <math>S_1</math> is noted
<math>\Sigma^c</math> (see figure  [[#figecran|figecran]]).
{{IMP/label|figecran}}
[[ Image: Ecran.png | center | frame |Names of the various surfaces for the considered diffraction problem.]]
The Electromagnetic signal that falls on <math>\Sigma</math> is assumed not to be
perturbed by the screen <math>S_c</math>: value of each component <math>U</math> of the
electromagnetic field is the value <math>U_{free}</math> of <math>U</math> without any screen. The value of <math>U</math> on the right hand side of <math>S_c</math> is assumed to be zero. Let us state the diffraction problem  ([#References|references]) (Rayleigh Sommerfeld diffraction problem): 
{{IMP/prob|
Given a function <math>U_{free}</math>, find a function <math>U</math> such that:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
(\Delta +k^2)U=0\mbox{ in  }\Omega
</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U=U_{free} \mbox{ on  }\Sigma
</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U=0\mbox{ on  }\Sigma^c
</math>}}
}}
Elementary solution of Helmholtz operator <math>\Delta +k^2</math> in <math>R^3</math> is
{{IMP/eq|<math>
G_M(M')=\frac{e^{jkr}}{4\pi r}
</math>}}
where <math>r=|MM'|</math>.
Green solution for our screen problem is obtained using images
method\index{images method} (see
section  [[secimage|secimage]]). It is solution of following problem:
{{IMP/prob|
Find  <math>u</math> such that:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
(\Delta +k^2)U=\delta_M\mbox{ in  }\Omega
</math>}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U=0\mbox{ on  }S_1=\Sigma^c\cup\Sigma^c
</math>}}
}}
This solution is:

{{IMP/label|eqgreendif}}
{{IMP/eq|<math>G_M(M')=\frac{1}{4\pi}(\frac{e^{jkr}}{r}+\frac{e^{jkr^s}}{r^s})</math>}}

with <math>r_s=|M_sM'|</math> where <math>M_s</math> is the symmetrical of <math>M</math> with respect to the
screen. Thus:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U(M)=\int_\Omega u(M')\delta_M(M') dM'=\int_\Omega
u(M')(\Delta+k^2)G_M(M')dM' 
</math>}}
Now using the fact that in <math>\Omega</math>, <math>\Delta U=-k^2U</math>:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\int_{\Omega}U(M')(\Delta+k^2)G_M(M') dM'=\int_{\Omega}(U(M')\Delta
G_M(M')-G_M(M')\Delta U(M')) dM'.
</math>}}
Applying Green's theorem, volume integral can be transformed to a surface
integral:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\int_{\Omega}(U\Delta G_M-G_M\Delta U) dM'=\int_{\mathcal S}(U\frac{\partial
G_M}{\partial n}-G_M\frac{\partial U}{\partial n}) ds'
</math>}}
where <math>n</math> is directed outwards surface <math>{\mathcal S}</math>.
Integral over <math>S=S_1+S_2</math> is reduced to an integral over
<math>S_1</math>  if the {\it Sommerfeld radiation condition}
\index{Sommerfeld radiation condition} is verified:

===Sommerfeld radiation condition===

Consider the particular case where surface <math>S_2</math> is the portion of sphere
centred en P with radius <math>R</math>. Let us look for a condition for the integral <math>I</math>
defined by:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
I=\int_{S_2}(U\frac{\partial G}{\partial n}-G\frac{\partial
U}{\partial n}) ds'
</math>}}
tends to zero when <math>R</math> tends to infinity. We have:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{\partial G}{\partial n}=(jk-\frac{1}{R})\frac{e^{jkR}}{R}\sim jkG,
</math>}}
thus
{{IMP/eq|<math>
I=\int_{\omega}\frac{e^{jkR}}{R}(\frac{\partial U}{\partial n}-jkU)R^2
d\omega
</math>}}
where <math>\omega</math> is the solid angle. If, in all directions, condition:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\lim_{R\rightarrow\infty}R(\frac{\partial U}{\partial n}-jkU)=0
</math>}}
is satisfied, then <math>I</math> is zero.
{{IMP/rem|
If <math>U</math> is a superposition of spherical waves, this condition is
verified\footnote{
Indeed if <math>U</math> is:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U=\frac{e^{jkR}}{R}
</math>}}
then
{{IMP/eq|<math>
R(\frac{\partial U}{\partial n}-jkU)=-\frac{e^{jkR}}{R}
</math>}}
tends to zero when <math>R</math> tends to infinity.
}.
}}

{{IMP/label|secHuyghens}}
===Huyghens principle===

From equation  [[#eqgreendif|eqgreendif]], <math>G</math> is zero on <math>S_1</math>.
\index{Huyghens principle}
We thus have:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U(M)=\frac{1}{4\pi}\int_{S_1}U(M')\frac{\partial G_M(M')}{\partial n}ds'
</math>}}
Now:
<center><math>\begin{matrix}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial n}&=&\cos
(n,r_{01})(jk-\frac{1}{r_{01}})\frac{e^{jkr_{01}}}{r_{01}}\\
&&-\cos(n,r'_{01})(jk-\frac{1}{r'_{01}})\frac{e^{jkr'_{01}}}{r'_{01}}
\end{matrix}</math></center>
where <math>r_{01}=MM'</math> and <math>r'_{01}=M_sM'</math>, <math>M'</math> belonging to <math>\Sigma</math> and
<math>M_s</math> being the symmetrical point of the point <math>M</math> where field <math>U</math> is
evaluated with respect to the screen. Thus:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
r_{01}=r'_{01}
</math>}}
and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\cos(n,r'_{01})=-\cos(n,r_{01})
</math>}}
One can evaluate:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{\partial G_M}{\partial n}=
2\cos(n,r_{01})(jk-\frac{1}{r_{01}})\frac{e^{jkr_{01}}}{r_{01}}
</math>}}
For <math>r_{01}</math> large, it yields\footnote{Introducing the wave lenght
<math>\lambda</math> defined by:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
k=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}
</math>}}
}:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
U(M)=\int_{S_1}U(M')\frac{j}{\lambda}\cos(n,r_{01})
\frac{e^{jkr_{01}}}{r_{01}}ds' 
</math>}}
This is the ''Huyghens principle''  :
{{IMP/prin|
*Light propagates from close to close. Each surface element reached by it    behaves like a secondary source that emits spherical wavelet with amplitude    proportional to the element surface.  
*Complex amplitude of light vibration in one point is the sum of complex    amplitudes produced by all secondary sources. It is said that vibrations    interfere to create the vibration at considered point.}}

Let <math>O</math> a point on <math>S_1</math>.
Fraunhoffer approximation \index{Fraunhoffer approximation}  consists in
approximating:  
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{e^{jkr_{01}}}{r_{01}}
</math>}}
by
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\frac{e^{jkR}}{R}e^{jk\vec R_M.\vec R_m /R}.
</math>}}
where  <math>R=OM</math>, <math>R_m=OM'</math>, <math>R_M=OM</math>.
Then amplitude Fourier transform\index{Fourier transform} of light on
<math>S_1</math> is observed at <math>M</math>.

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{FULLCHAPTERNAME}}]]

__toc__ ==Electromagnetic forces==
Postulates of electromagnetism have to be completed by another postulate that deals with interactions: {{IMP/postulat| In the case of a charged particle of charge <math>q</math>, Electromagnetic force applied to this particle is: {{IMP/eq|<math> f=qE+qv\wedge B </math>}} where <math>qE</math> is the electrical force (or Coulomb force) \index{Coulomb force} and <math>qv\wedge B</math> is the Lorentz force. \index{Lorentz force} }} This result can be generalized to continuous media using Poynting vector.\index{Poynting vector}
{{IMP/label|secenergemag}} ==Electromagnetic energy, Poynting vector==
Previous postulate using forces can be replaced by a "dual" postulate that uses energies: {{IMP/postulat| Consider a volume <math>V</math>. The vector <math>P=E\wedge H</math> is called Poynting vector. It is postulated that flux of vector <math>P</math> trough surface <math>S</math> delimiting volume <math>V</math>, oriented by a entering normal is equal to the Electromagnetic power <math>{\mathcal P}</math> given to this volume. }} Using Green's theorem, <math>{\mathcal P}</math> can be written as: {{IMP/eq|<math> {\mathcal P}=\int\!\!\!\int E\wedge H n ds =-\int\!\!\!\int\!\!\!\int \mbox{ div } (E\wedge H)d\tau </math>}} which yields, using Maxwell equations to: {{IMP/eq|<math> {\mathcal P}=\int\!\!\!\int\!\!\!\int H\frac{\partial B}{\partial t}+E.j+E\frac{\partial D}{\partial t}d\tau </math>}} Two last postulates are closely related. In fact we will show now that they basically say the same thing (even if Poynting vector form can be seen a bit more general).
Consider a point charge <math>q</math> in a field <math>E</math>. Let us move this charge of <math>dr</math>. Previous postulated states that to this displacement corresponds a variation of internal energy: {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int E\delta D d\tau </math>}} where <math>dD</math> is the variation of <math>D</math> induced by the charge displacement. {{IMP/thm| Internal energy variation is: {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=-f \delta r </math>}} where <math>f</math> is the electrical force applied to the charge. }} {{IMP/pf| In the static case, <math>E</math> field has conservative circulation (<math>\mbox{ rot } E=0</math>) so it derives from a potential. \medskip Let us write energy conservation equation: {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int E\delta D d\tau </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int- \mbox{ grad } (V) \delta D d\tau </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int V \mbox{ div }(\delta D) d\tau-\int \mbox{ div }(V\delta D) d\tau </math>}} Flow associated to divergence of <math>V\delta D</math> is zero in all the space, indeed <math>D</math> decreases as <math>1/r^2</math> and <math>V</math> as <math>1/r</math> and surface increases as <math>r^2</math>. So: {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int V \delta \rho d\tau </math>}} Let us move charge of <math>\delta r</math>. Charge distribution goes from <math>q\delta(r)</math> to <math>q\delta(r+dr)</math> where <math>\delta(r)</math> is Dirac distribution. We thus have <math>d \rho(r)=q(\delta(r+\delta r)-\delta(r))</math>. So: ,{{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\int\!\!\!\int\!\!\!\int qV(r)(\delta(r+\delta r)-\delta(r)) d\tau </math>}} thus {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=qV(r+\delta r)-qV(r) </math>}} {{IMP/eq|<math> \delta U=\mbox{ grad }(qV)\delta r </math>}} Variation is finally <math>\delta U=-fdr</math>. Moreover, we prooved that: {{IMP/eq|<math> f=-\mbox{ grad }(qV)=qE </math>}} }}
[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{FULLCHAPTERNAME}}]]

{{IMP/exo|{{IMP/label|exoeqhelmoltz}}
Assume constitutive relations to be:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
D(r,t)=\epsilon(r,t) * E(r,t)
</math>}}
where <math>*</math> represents temporal convolution\index{convolution} (value of
<math>D(r,t)</math> field at time <math>t</math> S
depends on values of <math>E</math> at preceeding times) and
{{IMP/eq|<math>
H=\frac{B}{\mu_0}
</math>}}
Show that in harmonical regime (<math>E(r,t)={\mathcal E}(r)e^{i\omega t}</math>) and without
any charges <math>{\mathcal E}(r)</math> field verifies ''Helmholtz equation'' :
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\Delta {\mathcal E}+k^{2}{\mathcal E}=0.
</math>}}
Give the expression of <math>k^{2}</math>.
}}

{{IMP/exo|
Show (see  ([#References|references])) that function <math>V_{e(r)}</math>: 
{{IMP/eq|<math>
V_e(r)=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0 r}
</math>}}
is solution of
Maxwell--Gauss equation, {\it i. e } it verifies:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
\Delta V_e=\frac{\delta}{\epsilon_0}
</math>}}
}}

{{IMP/exo|
Proove charge conservation equation  [[eqconsdelacharge|eqconsdelacharge]] from Maxwell
equations. 
}}

{{IMP/exo|
Give the expression of electrical potential created by quadripole <math>Q_{ij}</math>.
}}

{{IMP/exo|
Show from the expression of magnetic energy that force acting on a point
charge <math>q</math> with velocity <math>v</math> is:
{{IMP/eq|<math>
f=qv\wedge B
</math>}}

}}

